>design your own /hmofa/ game
Given I'm into pretty hard sci fi, I think I'd break it into a couple of major phases.

First phase would be something of an evolution-generator, but with gene mod technology. So, you would be something of a civilization that has discovered a habitable planet, but it is in a similar state as Earth about 2 or 20 million years after the big dinosaur extinction event 65 million years ago. You need to planet form /terrform so that it would be habitable by humans in the "near future." There would be several random problems to solve (adjusting atmosphere, land-to-sea ratio, etc.) and the genetic mods you make to existing species would be affected by their adaptation to new planetary conditions.

Alternatively, the player could choose a dinosaur epoch and (try to) save them from an extinction event.

Regardless, phase two would be running a few thousand years' wort of simulation on the news epcies, monitoring as they develop, make adjustments, see how successful they are. Ideally, there would be half a dozen or more species of sapient anthros arising and you could interact with them as frm tribes and pass into stone & bronze age civilizations. Player gets less and less control at this point because you have to ride the events set in motion.

Human colonization is about to arrive.

Phase three, humans bring highly advanced space-faring tech & civilization. Now player is fully immersed in playing the world that has been designed, living with what went right & wrong. Making friends & companions amongst the anthro peoples, and finding a waifur (or harem thereof) as they adventure through the world and encounter & solve wars, conflicts, build civ, integrate humans, build a new space-faring colony to go forth into the galaxy and start all over again.

You "win" this game when your first hyper-light colony craft, now populated with humans and an uplifted group of anthros, launches to a new, promising star to do it all over again.

Anonymous Mon 07 Mar 2022 06:12:00 No.46010089 Report
Quoted By: >>46010290 >>46010408
>>46009355
I liked it a lot since it wasn't just some MC falling into a perfect life, but a somewhat probable look at what would happen if your average person with access to an encyclopedia got dropped into an alien society that was far behind our own in terms of technology and personal rights. The alien species actually thinks in an alien way, and the MC attempting to maintain his "human" life is a major source of conflict all the way to the end. His jokes fall flat, he's often not sure if his "friends" actually like him or just want access to his info, and his attempts at romantic relationships almost get him killed. The world building is very well done, to the point it almost feels like a guided tour of Anthro Feline Land.
I also liked the sense of progression. He starts off trying to be friendly and trusting, and winds up permanently disfigured from it. By the third and final book, he's carrying his own pistols and wearing an overcoat with steel plates since he's finally figured out EVERYONE wants him and what he has. He originally keeps thinking of the aliens as furry humans, and is often surprised by what he perceives as coldness from them. By the end of the third book he can trade barbs with politicians without issue. He gets thrashed pretty good in the first book with permanent scars, and in the last book he takes down a stream of assassins while his nearest scrape is when he almost freezes in a river in the middle of winter after having a bridge blown out from under him.
>the summary posted sure as hell isn't comfy
He helps the woman he actually cares about, turns a constant thorn in his side into a sexual partner, and found a solution to getting fur in his mouth. What isn't comfy there?
